{"id":"astro-ph/0002302","submitter":"Viki Joergens","authors":"V. Joergens (1,2), H.C. Spruit (1) and R.G.M. Rutten (3,4) ((1) MPI\n  f\"ur Astrophysik, Garching; (2) MPI f\"ur Extraterrestrische Physik, Garching;\n  (3) Netherlands Foundation for Research in Astronomy; (4) Royal Greenwich\n  Observatory, La Palma)","title":"Spirals and the size of the disk in EX Dra","comments":"accepted (A&A Letter)","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Observations at high spectral and temporal resolution are presented of the\ndwarf nova EX Dra in outburst. The disk seen in the He I line reconstructed by\nDoppler tomography shows a clear two-armed spiral pattern pointing to spiral\nshocks in the disk. The Balmer and He II maps also give evidence for the\npresence of spirals. The eclipse as seen in the red continuum indicates a disk\nradius of 0.31 times the orbital separation, which might be large enough to\nexplain the observed spiral shocks through excitation by the tidal field of the\nsecondary. The eclipse in the Balmer line profiles, well resolved in our\nobservations, indicates a somewhat smaller disk size (0.25). We discuss the\npossibility that this is related to an optical depth effect in the lines.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 15 Feb 2000 16:49:53 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 15 Mar 2000 10:25:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
