{"id":"nucl-th/0002039","submitter":"David A. Brown","authors":"David A. Brown, Sergei Y. Panitkin, and George F. Bertsch","title":"Extracting particle freeze-out phase-space densities and entropies from\n  sources imaged in heavy-ion reactions","comments":"14 pages, final version, to appear PRC. Fixed typos, added refs. for\n  last section, added discussions of imaging and d/p ratios","journal-ref":"Phys.Rev. C62 (2000) 014904","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevC.62.014904","report-no":"DOE/ER/40561-82-INT00-INT","categories":"nucl-th hep-ph nucl-ex","license":null,"abstract":"  The space-averaged phase-space density and entropy per particle are both\nfundamental observables which can be extracted from the two-particle\ncorrelation functions measured in heavy-ion collisions. Two techniques have\nbeen proposed to extract the densities from correlation data: either by using\nthe radius parameters from Gaussian fits to meson correlations or by using\nsource imaging, which may be applied to any like pair correlation. We show that\nthe imaging and Gaussian fits give the same result in the case of meson\ninterferometry. We discuss the concept of an equivalent instantaneous source on\nwhich both techniques rely. We also discuss the phase-space occupancy and\nentropy per particle. Finally, we propose an improved formula for the\nphase-space occupancy that has a more controlled dependence on the uncertainty\nof the experimentally measured source functions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 15 Feb 2000 22:42:01 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 5 Apr 2000 18:05:23 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-06"}
